6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX funding rates are calculated using oracle prices and open interest imbalances in GLP pools, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to 0.01% hourly. RabbitX uses traditional order book mechanics where funding rates reflect the premium between perpetual and mark prices, calculated from their smaller but more price-sensitive user base. GMX rates tend to be more stable due to deeper liquidity but may not reflect true market sentiment as effectively as RabbitX's order-driven model."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rates for arbitrage?","answer":"GMX typically offers more predictable funding rates due to its oracle-based model and deeper liquidity, while RabbitX may present more volatile opportunities due to its smaller user base and order book dynamics."},{"question":"How do trading fees impact funding rate arbitrage profitability?","answer":"RabbitX's 0.02%/0.05% fees versus GMX's 0.05%/0.07% fees can significantly impact short-term arbitrage strategies. The 0.02-0.03% fee difference requires funding rates to be proportionally higher on RabbitX to maintain profitability."},{"question":"What are the main technical risks when arbitraging between these platforms?","answer":"GMX carries oracle manipulation risks and potential GLP pool imbalances, while RabbitX presents early-stage protocol risks and potential liquidity gaps due to its smaller market size."},{"question":"How does settlement speed affect funding arbitrage execution?","answer":"Both platforms settle hourly funding, but RabbitX's Starknet architecture offers faster position adjustments with zero gas costs, while GMX requires Arbitrum gas fees for position management."}]}]
